eved</i> ‘head’. See also   Black  .","nickname from Middle English <i>blak</i> ‘black’ + <i>hod</i> ‘hood’."],"variants":[{"name":"Black","meanings":["English and Scottish: chiefly from Middle English <i>blak(e)</i> ‘black’ (Old English <i>blæc</i>, <i>blaca</i>), a nickname given from the earliest times to a swarthy or dark-haired man. However, Middle English <i>blac</i> also meant ‘pale, wan’, a reflex of Old English <i>blāc</i> ‘pale, white’ with a shortened vowel. Compare   Blatch   and   Blick  . With rare exceptions it is impossible to disambiguate these antithetical senses in Middle English surnames. The same difficulty arises with   Blake   and   Block  .","Scottish: in Gaelic-speaking areas this name was adopted as a translation of the epithet <i>dubh</i> ‘dark, black-(haired)’, or of various other names based on Gaelic <i>dubh</i> ‘black’, see   Duff  .","Americanized form (translation into English) of various European surnames directly or indirectly derived from the adjective meaning ‘black, dark’, for example German and Jewish   Schwarz   and Slavic surnames beginning with <i>Čern-</i>, <i>Chern-</i> (see   Chern   and   Cherne  ), <i>Chorn-</i>, <i>Crn-</i> or <i>Czern-</i>."]}]},{"name":"Margery","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual medieval vernacular form of   Margaret   (now also commonly spelled   Marjorie  ). This form of the name is preserved in the nursery rhyme ‘See-saw, Margery Daw’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":3,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":16,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":25,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Margery Blankett was born in 1312, in England as the daughter of John Blankett. She had at least 1 daughter with Walter de Raan. She died in Oxfordshire, England."},"et":{"1312–":"1312–Surnud","1312–Female":"1312–Surnud","1305–1372":"1305–1372","1337–Female":"1337–Surnud","1287–Male":"1287–Surnud","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1312":"1312","1453":"1453","1287":"1287","1372":"1372","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Amersham, Buckinghamshire, England":"Amersham, Buckinghamshire, England","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"1312–":"1312–Kuollut","1312–Female":"1312–Kuollut","1305–1372":"1305–1372","1337–Female":"1337–Kuollut","1287–Male":"1287–Kuollut","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1312":"1312","1453":"1453","1287":"1287","1372":"1372","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Amersham, Buckinghamshire, England":"Amersham, Buckinghamshire, England","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England","England":"England"},"fr":{"1312–":"1312–Décédée","1312–Female":"1312–Décédée","1305–1372":"1305–1372","1337–Female":"1337–Décédée","1287–Male":"1287–Décédé","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1312":"1312","1453":"1453","1287":"1287","1372":"1372","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Amersham, Buckinghamshire, England":"Amersham, Buckinghamshire, Angleterre","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, Angleterre","England":"Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Margery Blankett